{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 16:29:55.238354", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf lab\n(assets examined: host_1_1, host_1_2, host_2_1, host_2_2, leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1; reachability matrix)\n\n1) Executive summary\n- There is an L2 connectivity anomaly affecting the hosts on leaf_1 (host_1_1 — 10.0.0.1 and host_1_2 — 10.0.0.2). Those hosts cannot ARP/communicate to peers in the 10.0.0.0/24 network (pings fail with \"Destination Host Unreachable\" and ARP entries show FAILED).\n- leaf_1 shows the OVS bridge device (ovs-system / the Open vSwitch datapath) in a DOWN state while its physical ports are individually UP. This mismatch prevents host-facing ports from participating in L2 forwarding, causing the observed failures.\n- leaf_2 and spine_1 appear healthy (management addresses present and traffic counters show normal RX/TX activity).\n\n2) Symptoms observed\n- host_1_1 -> host_1_2: 100% packet loss; ping returned \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=N Destination Host Unreachable\".\n- host_1_2 -> host_2_1: 100% packet loss; same \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\n- ip neigh on host_1_1: \"10.0.0.2 dev eth0 FAILED\" (ARP failed).\n- ip neigh on host_1_2: \"10.0.0.5 dev eth0 FAILED\".\n- /proc/net/dev on host_1_1 and host_1_2: eth0 shows RX packets = 0 (hosts are sending but not receiving).\n- ethtool on host_1_1 eth0: Link detected: yes (host NIC sees link).\n\n3) Key evidence (tool outputs / observations)\n- Reachability matrix: many host-to-host entries are unknown but where tests ran they show failures involving host_1_1/host_1_2.\n- Ping (host_1_1 -> host_1_2):\n  - 4 transmitted, 0 received, +4 errors, 100% packet loss; kernel reports unreachable.\n- host_1_1 (ip neigh and /proc/net/dev):\n  - \"10.0.0.2 dev eth0 FAILED\"\n  - eth0: RX packets 0, TX packets non-zero (host transmitting but no responses).\n- host_1_2 (ip neigh and /proc/net/dev):\n  - \"10.0.0.5 dev eth0 FAILED\"\n  - eth0: RX packets 0, TX packets non-zero.\n- host_1_1 ethtool eth0:\n  - Link detected: yes; Speed 10000Mb/s (NIC link present).\n- leaf_1 network state:\n  - Several physical ports exist (eth0..eth6) and are shown as \"master ovs-system\" (i.e., enslaved), but the ovs-system interface and the bridge name entry are in state DOWN:\n    - ovs-system: state DOWN (in ip addr listing)\n    - leaf_1 (OVS bridge?) flags show state DOWN\n  - Per-port counters on leaf_1:\n    - eth0 (host_1_1 side): RX packets = 0, TX = 0\n    - eth1 (host_1_2 side): RX small (12) but TX 0\n    - other ports (eth4, eth5, eth6) show large RX counts (management/spine-facing traffic arrives), indicating upstream is getting traffic.\n- leaf_2 and spine_1:\n  - Have management IPs (20.0.0.4 and 20.0.0.1) and show substantial RX/TX counts — no evidence of the same failure there.\n\n4) Localization of faulty component(s)\n- Primary implicated device: leaf_1 (the OVS switch/bridge instance).\n  - Evidence: ovs-system (the OVS bridge device) is DOWN on leaf_1; host-facing physical ports appear enslaved to that bridge but the bridge itself is not functioning; host-facing port counters show no received frames from leaf side; ARP fails at hosts.\n- Affected endpoints: host_1_1 (10.0.0.1) and host_1_2 (10.0.0.2).\n  - Evidence: both have eth0 up and link detected at NIC level, but both show RX = 0 and ARP entries for peers marked FAILED.\n- Devices not implicated: leaf_2 and spine_1 appear operational (they have management IPs and normal traffic counters).\n\n5) Root-cause analysis (most likely)\n- The host NICs are physically up (ethtool shows link), but L2 forwarding is not occurring across leaf_1 because the Open vSwitch datapath/bridge on leaf_1 (ovs-system) is DOWN or not operational. Because the bridge/datapath is down, frames sent by the hosts are not forwarded or ARP replies are not received — resulting in ARP timeouts and the kernel reporting destination unreachable.\n- Supporting interpretation:\n  - Hosts can drive their NICs (TX non-zero), but no RX frames arrive — consistent with switch-side forwarding not delivering frames to host ports.\n  - Upstream/spine traffic is present on leaf_1's other ports (eth4/eth5/eth6), so the leaf device sees traffic, but the bridge internal state prevents delivering traffic to host-facing ports.\n  - The ovs-system device state DOWN suggests either the OVS user-space daemon or OVS kernel datapath is down/misaligned on leaf_1, or the OVS bridge config was modified/unloaded, leaving physical NICs attached but the datapath not forwarding.\n\n6) Impact\n- Hosts attached to leaf_1 (host_1_1 and host_1_2) cannot communicate with other hosts in the 10.0.0.0/24 subnet and cannot reach hosts attached to other leaves (e.g., host_2_1/host_2_2), resulting in full L2 isolation for these hosts.\n- The rest of the fabric (leaf_2, spine_1) appears operational, so issue is localized to leaf_1 domain.\n\n7) Additional notes / suggested next investigative checks (no remediation given)\n- Check OVS/daemon state and configuration on leaf_1 (ovs-vsctl show, systemctl status openvswitch, dmesg / kernel OVS datapath logs) to confirm whether OVS is running and the bridge datapath is up.\n- Inspect bridge and port bindings on leaf_1 to confirm the host-facing ports are attached to the datapath and not in a DOWN administrative state.\n- Collect ovs-ofctl/ovs-vsctl and system logs from leaf_1 to pinpoint why ovs-system is DOWN (e.g., service crash, datapath removal, misconfiguration).\n- If needed, capture frames on the host-facing interface on leaf_1 to confirm whether upstream frames reach the switch port but are not delivered to the host.\n\n8) Conclusion\n- There is a clear L2 forwarding failure localized at leaf_1 (OVS instance). Hosts host_1_1 and host_1_2 are isolated due to ARP failures and zero RX traffic. The likely root cause is the OVS bridge/datapath on leaf_1 being down or non-functional despite physical links being up. Leaf_2 and spine_1 are not exhibiting these faults.\n\nIf yo